<style>
    #more {
        display: none;
    }

    #checkbox:checked + #more {
        display: block !important;
    }

    tr:nth-child(2n) {
        background-color: #0003;
    }

    table {
        background: #00fff9;
        border-spacing: 0;
        border: 2px solid #000;
    }

    td {
        padding: 2px;
    }

    tr:nth-child(1) {
        background: #1ab3b2;
        border-bottom: 0;
        text-align: center;
    }

    tr:nth-child(2) {
        background: #1ab3b2;
        border-top: 0;
    }

    label {
        display: contents;
        text-decoration: underline;
        color: #0006ff;
    }

    #content {
        padding: 10px
    }
</style>
<div id="content">
    {#await fetcher()}
        Fetching data... (This usually takes up to 30 seconds)
    {:then data}
        <table>
            <tr>
                <td colspan="3">
                    Keyboard shortcuts
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Key
                </td>
                <td>
                    Function
                </td>
                <td>
                    Source
                </td>
            </tr>
            {#each data as shortcut}
                <tr>
                    <td>
                        {shortcut.key}
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        {shortcut.value}
                    </td>
                    <td>
                        <a href={shortcut.origin.url}>{shortcut.origin.title}</a>
                    </td>
                </tr>
            {/each}
        </table>
    {:catch err}
        Something went wrong.
        Error: {err}
    {/await}
    <div>
        This page was auto-generated. I cannot control the results, and they might be wrong. <label id="label" for="checkbox">How it works</label>
    </div>
    <input type="checkbox" hidden id="checkbox" on:click={smoothScroller}>
    <div id="more">
        This page connects to my Heroku backend. It does the following things:
        <ul>
            <li>Scrape Google results for "keyboard shortcuts" with apify</li>
            <li>Download 10 search results</li>
            <li>Parse the results with a lot of Regular Expressions and Javascript</li>
            <li>Send the results as JSON as a REST API (you can see the raw data <a
                    href="https://shortcutting.herokuapp.com/sync">here</a>)</li>
        </ul>
        This page then gets the results from the REST API by using the Fetch API, and then it uses Svelte and JS/CSS/HTML to
        display it as a table.
        You can see the whole project's code (Heroku backend AND Svelte frontend) on <a
